name: 3,4-dimethylbiphenyl
Reason: The target compound, 3,4-dimethylbiphenyl, has two key structural components: the biphenyl base and two methyl groups. The biphenyl unit, consisting of two benzene rings, can be considered as having twice the influence of a single benzene ring. A single benzene ring has a melting point around 5.5 ºC. Doubling this contribution for the two fused benzene rings would give a baseline of 11 ºC. Each methyl group attached to the benzene ring will raise the melting point due to an increase in molecular weight and slight increase in molecular symmetry. A single methyl group in a mono-substituted benzene typically raises the melting point by about 20ºC. However, in a polycyclic system the effect could be somewhat attenuated due to steric hindrance, so we might estimate the increase to be 15ºC per methyl group. The combined effect of two methyl groups would then be an addition of 30ºC. Combining the baseline estimate for the biphenyl (11 ºC) with the contributions from the two methyl groups (15 ºC each), we arrive at a predicted melting point.
